														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1623136">
									

<p>I think I might just be the wrong audience for this joke, because I work with both PCs and hand-cobbled circuitry daily.</p>
<p>It has been proven to me time and time again, to the point where I can't deny it, that when a bit of electronics is &quot;acting up&quot; it is <em>always</em> an ID/OT error. That is, the problem exists between the keyboard and the chair. GIGO, and other cliche tech support tropes.</p>
<p>Circuits and programs always do the same thing, they have no choice. You get different results because humans are not designed for precision work, we only <em>think</em> we do the same thing every time because our minds are as fuzzy as that forgotten slice of pizza under the couch. Computers do only what we tell them to do, not what we meant to tell them to do.</p>

