			<div class="content" id="post-content-1623395">
									

<p>An ex, who was really into computer stuff, once told me that there are stochastic processes even in the most reliable hardrware (and that each modern circuit is unique due to, uhhh&#8230; let me recall the quote, &quot;random operational parameter fluctuations due to presence of randomly distributed dopant atoms&quot;. Also, migration of dopant atoms in memory chippery due to particular usage patterns is kinda a big thing with paranoid &quot;spy tech&quot; boffins, some guy had an article about recovering data from &quot;dopant migration imprints&quot;, I think (which is kinda crazy, but if you're curious, I can phone my ex and try to find out the names of relevant papers)</p>
<p>Also, some types of programming errors cause what can can be, from &quot;user side&quot; of things, pretty hard to distinguish from a classic description of intermittent glitch (they will eventually be reproduced, but that's a bit of a cold comfort when you face something that was &quot;wrong a moment ago, but right now&quot; ;-) )</p>

