			<div class="content" id="post-content-1623411">
									

<p>Doping imputities make each circuit unique on a molecular level, and it's not even uncommon for impurities to cause a circuit to malfunction. But that circuit will malfunction the same way every time. A given electrical current passes through a particular medium in a certain way, it can't change it's path and pattern anymore than the sun can set in the west.</p>
<p>Dopant migration is one of those things that's technically true, but doesn't mean what it seems to. The details are very boring, but suffice to say that recreating data from dopant migration is like recreating all the e-mails you've ever written by examing the wear patterns on your fingerprints from the keyboard. Theoretically, it's possible, but mind-blowingly unlikely.</p>
<p>I get what you're saying about the programming errors though. Point of view matters. I just don't think that way about it because I spend so much time working at the machine code level. The programmer is just some other user that messed with my machine before I got to it.</p>
<p>Like I said up-thread, I think I'm just the wrong audience for this.</p>

