					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/chazzk" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1203158); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1203158&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183435" alt="ChazzK" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1203158)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/chazzk" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1203158); return false;" >ChazzK</a></span> <span class="odate time_1354031154 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">27 Nov 2012 15:45</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1629217">
									

<p>The problem with intermittent problems is that they are, by nature, intermittent. It may be difficult or impossible to recreate *reliably*. Case in point: the first time I had a power supply die on me. My computer would, at seemingly random intervals, shut off. Sometimes it would be after being on for hours, sometimes Windows wasn't even loaded yet; sometimes it would be during incredibly heavy loads, sometimes it was when it was sitting idle with nothing running but background stuff. It turned out that there had been a small bit of&#8230; Something wrong with one of the wires, I honestly can't remember now if it was corrosion or pinched or loose or what. What was happening was that, due to vibrations, it would *very* occasionally wiggle just right to short out; once we found that, if I had been capable (or willing) to run it with the power supply open and exposed, I could have recreated it every time, but there was no way to actually tell before hand.</p>
<p>THAT, is where the seemingly random, intermittent problems most usually come from. Not a part that's *failed*, but one that is just on the very edge of complete failure.</p>

							</div>

								
					
