														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1629070">
									

<p>From where I sit, which is in a network operations center, where my job is to watch for alerts for all sorts of software, networking, and hardware errors from datacenters full of servers, computers act up for many, many reasons, most of which can be abstracted to, operating environments are dynamic, not static. The hard drive that was 84% full is now 85% full. Something changed the boot order since the last reboot, so that one application tried to pull a config file down from another server before the network connection was up. That Web server is responding slowly, because an application is indexing the documents and using a lot of disk I/O.</p>
<p>I was making a joke above about system logs. Look at the system logs for any system that's apparently running smoothly, and see how many warnings and error messages there are. Operating systems are complex and messy, and sometimes processes conflict with each other or run out of storage space.</p>

							</div>

								
